  "articleSummary": "The article argues that \"generative UI\" is a multifaceted concept often conflated into a single term, advocating for a layered framework to clarify its architecture. It identifies four distinct layers—**product shell**, **UI composition model**, **runtime/transport**, and **agent/tool backend**—to untangle the ecosystem, emphasizing that tools like AG-UI, A2UI, or json-render operate at different levels. The core thesis critiques the confusion caused by overlapping definitions, framing generative UI as a spectrum balancing **developer control** (e.g., prebuilt components) and **agent freedom** (e.g., dynamic HTML generation), with trade-offs in usability and security. Intended for developers and architects building LLM-powered apps, the piece uses metaphors like \"training wheels\" for early chat interfaces and a \"map\" to visualize the landscape, adopting an analytical tone to dissect technical choices.",
